Day 3: Fundamental Linux Commands

1- To view what's written in a file?
ANS: cat filename
Replace "filename" with the name of the file you want to view.
2- To change the access permissions of files?
ANS: chmod permissions filename
"permissions" represent the new permissions you want to set, which can be expressed in various ways. "filename" is the name of the file for which you want to change the permissions.
3- To check which commands you have run till now?
ANS: history
This will display a list of the most recent commands you've executed, along with corresponding line numbers.
4- To remove a directory/ Folder in Linux?
ANS: 'rmdir' or 'rm' (rmdir directory_name) and for file (rm filename)
5- To create a fruits.txt file in Linux?
ANS: touch fruits.txt
This will create an empty file with the specified name.
6- Add content in devops.txt (One in each line) - Apple, Mango, Banana, Cherry, Kiwi, Orange, Guava in Linux?
ANS: echo -e "Apple\nMango\nBanana\nCherry\nKiwi\nOrange\nGuava" > devops.txt
This command will add each fruit on a separate line in the "devops.txt" file.
Alternatively, you can use a text editor like nano to manually add the content.
(nano devops.txt)
